e", "prob": 0.9963369369506836, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1279}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6778"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9949737787246704, "span": {"begin": 1421, "end": 1426}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969532489776611, "span": {"begin": 1427, "end": 1429}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2625"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GATA-3 mRNA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9982516765594482, "span": {"begin": 1452, "end": 1463}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "immune cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8139117956161499, "span": {"begin": 1528, "end": 1540}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2625"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GATA3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.997614860534668, "span": {"begin": 1542, "end": 1547}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9907221794128418, "span": {"begin": 1552, "end": 1561}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3169"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FOXA1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9930700659751892, "span": {"begin": 1598, "end": 1603}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "heterochromatic enhancer regions", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.9004444479942322, "span": {"begin": 1642, "end": 1674}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER&alpha; target", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9360165596008301, "span": {"begin": 1678, "end": 1694}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.48926690220832825, "span": {"begin": 1695, "end": 1700}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3169"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FOXA1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9957177042961121, "span": {"begin": 1831, "end": 1836}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1840, "end": 1842}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "chromatin", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8588403463363647, "span": {"begin": 1887, "end": 1896}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2625"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GATA3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9910763502120972, "span": {"begin": 1942, "end": 1947}}], "text": "The hormone binding domain (HBD) of the ER&alpha; is required not only for binding ligand but also to form stable homodimers of the protein and mediate transcriptional activation by the receptor.&nbsp; There are two ligand-dependent signaling pathway.&nbsp; One is &ldquo;classical&rdquo; and the other is &ldquo;tethered&rdquo; pathway.&nbsp; A direct genomic interaction occurs between the ER ligand complex and specific sequences of DNA known as estrogen response elements (ERE) (Parker MG. 1993, Goldstein RA. 1993, Sasson S. 1991, Brandt ME. 1997). &nbsp;Transcriptional activation by ER&alpha; is mediated by two distinct activation functions: the constitutively active AF-1 domain, located in the N-terminal domain of the receptor protein, and the ligand-dependent AF-2 domain, located in the C-terminal domain of the receptor protein (Delaunay F. 2000). &nbsp;This is called &ldquo;classical&rdquo; signaling pathway.&nbsp; In addition to above classical mechanism, ligand-activated ER&alpha; interact with other transcription factor complexes and bind to non-EREs by attaching to other transcription factors and not with ERE directly. (Carolyn MK. 2001).&nbsp; This is also called &ldquo;tethered&rdquo; signaling pathway.&nbsp; The transcription factors GATA3 and STAT6 are essential for the establishment and/or maintenance of these interactions (Spilianakis and Flavell, 2004).&nbsp; In the tethered pathway, STAT6-ER fusion protein induce GATA-3 mRNA expression.&nbsp;&nbsp;Furthermore, in mammary gland but not in immune cells, GATA3 and ER&alpha; regulate each other and, along with FOXA1, can nucleate a remodeling complex at heterochromatic enhancer regions of ER&alpha; target genes, leading to the opening and epigenetic marking of sites for active transcription (Eeckhoute J. 2007, Kong SL. 2011).&nbsp; Alone, FOXA1 or ER&alpha; are not sufficient to fully open the chromatin, supporting a bona fide pioneer activity for GATA3 (Eeckhoute J. 2007, Kong SL. 2011).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:23:26 +0000 2026"}